Hybrid, Electric, Diesel? How has miles per gallon changed throughout the years?

By : Joel Samuel

Intro / Motivation¶

In our world today, the use of cars has become ordinary and often neccessary in order to survive. But the basic function of the car is to take us further than we ever could just walking. How have we advanced? Are our cars getting better in terms of the miles we get per gallon? The better we get with our miles per gallon, the better our environment becomes as well. We all have heard about alternate fuels for our cars, but how effective are they? Diesel, hybrid, and electric vehicles are the most popular alternate fuels when it comes to cars. How effecient are they really and how have they changed throughout the years? Are we getting better? In this tutorial we aim to answer these questions.
I believe that hybrid cars, since it utilizes both gas and electricity, that it would be able to get cars to go the farthest.

Documentation and Dataset Zip File :https://www.fueleconomy.gov/feg/ws/index.shtml#ft2

*Note : electrical cars are measured in mpge, miles per gallon equivalent of electricity

Data Collection¶

FuelEconomy.gov has a lot of data on cars and their fuel economy information. This information is provided by the US Department of energy. In order to get the dataset you first need to download the csv file from https://www.fueleconomy.gov/feg/ws/index.shtml#ft2, a file called vehicle.csv (unzipped). This csv file contains the fuel ecnomy information for 1984 - current model year vehicles. We can find the documentation for this csv file if you scroll down. Once downloaded use pandas in order to store the data into a nice clean dataframe

Data Management / Representation¶

Now we trim the dataframe to get the neccessary information needed to make our assumptions. First we sort the values by year and then by make in order to see the data based on the years. Then retrieve the data needed from the table, such as the make, model, mileage, etc. Hybrid and electric cars only started to coming into use 'lately' (late 90's) so we then trim the data to years only past 1995 to help make the data easier to look at and we still get data that pertains to the problem.

The dataframe should have the following features:
Make :manufacturer
Model :model
AtvType :type of alternative fuel or advanced technology vehicle
City08 :city MPG
Year :model year

In [3]:
# Getting only needed columns
df_trim = df[['make','model','atvType','city08','year']].copy()
# Sorting the dataframe by year and make
df_trim = df_trim.sort_values(by=['year','make'])
# Dropping all years before 1995
df_trim = df_trim.drop(df_trim[df_trim['year'] < 1995].index)
df_trim.head()

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Now to explore the data: I first plotted all the data and added a regression line to see how all cars fare in terms of miles per gallon through the years. We can see that in this plot how the average miles per gallon is for all cars. The average has always been around 20 miles per gallon. We also see a gradual increase from just below 20 miles per gallon in 1995 to just above 20 miles per gallon. This means that throughout all these years, while there is an increase in average miles per gallon, most manufacturers have not put much energy into increasing the average miles per gallon by a good amount.

In [5]:
# Iterate through each year
plt.subplots(figsize = (20,10))
for year in years:
    # Get the table for that year
    curr = df_trim.drop(df_trim[df_trim['year'] != year].index)
    # Plot the data for each year and the mpg
    plt.plot(curr['year'],curr['city08'],'.')
# Making plot pretty
plt.xlabel('Years')
plt.ylabel('Miles Per Gallon')
plt.title('Car Miles Per Gallon through the Years')
# Fitting best fit line
m,b = np.polyfit(df_trim['year'],df_trim['city08'],1)
plt.plot(df_trim['year'], m*(df_trim['year'])+b,color='yellow')
plt.savefig('CarMilesPerGallon.png')

Overall Look¶

I then plotted the data but annotated where the diesel, hybrid, and electric vehicles in order to see how they fare against other regular cars. This was a little hard to see so I made three plots annotating each individual type. We can see pretty clearly already that electrical can be more than 10x better that the regression line. Hybrids went up to 3x better than regression line but at the same time, as time progressed, we see more and more hybrids get closer to the regression line and sometimes even below it. Diesel on the other hand, while a little effective in earlier years, mainly sticks to the regression line and while there are some diesel vehicles that go up to 1.5x the regression line, we can see that diesel is not too different than most cars when it comes to miles per gallon

In [7]:
# Getting the alternate fuel types
atvTypes =['Diesel','Hybrid','EV']
plt.subplots(figsize = (20,30))
# Iterate through each year
for year in years:
    # Getting the data for each year
    curr = df_trim.drop(df_trim[df_trim['year'] != year].index)
    # Plotting the mpg data for each year
    plt.plot(curr['year'],curr['city08'],'.')
    # Annotating each fuel type in the year
    for index, row in curr.iterrows():
        if row['atvType'] in atvTypes:
            plt.annotate(row['atvType'],(df_trim['year'][index],df_trim['city08'][index]))
# Making plot pretty

plt.ylabel('Miles Per Gallon')
plt.title('Car Miles Per Gallon through the Years')

    # Get the table for that year

    # Plot the data for each year and the mpg
    plt.plot(curr['year'],curr['city08'],'.')

plt.title('Alternate Fuel Cars Miles Per Gallon through the Years')

plt.plot(df_types['year'], m*(df_types['year'])+b,color='yellow')
plt.savefig('CarMilesPerGallon.png')

We can now test our hypothesis on if year has a relationship with overall miles per gallon between our vehicle types. We can reject the null hypothesis of no relationship between year and miles per gallon with our linear regression model. After fitting the model to our data, we end up with a p value of 0.000 which means that our data is statistically significant and there is a relationship between miles per gallon and year.

Insights / Conclusion¶

For all cars, we see that there is an increase of miles per gallon throughout the years. However, there is not a significant change for the average car miles per gallon. We see that the average car fuel economy stays around 20 miles per gallon from 1995 to today. Diesel cars while slightly better than the average car fuel economy, has not increased by much throughout the years. The one that surprised me was the hybrid cars. While there are some hybrid cars that boast great fuel economy, there are also a good amount of hybrid cars that are below the average car fuel economy. So we see that in the case for most cars, there has not been significant improvement through the years. This shows that in the case for most cars, they are not looking to enhance its performance when it comes to miles per gallon. The only car that has significant increase was the electrical car. We can see very clearly, that electrical cars have been improving in terms of miles per gallon throughout the years. We can see that out of all the alternate fuel types, electrical vehicles are by far the most efficient car and have improved the most throughout the years. Diesel has improved throughout the years, but not by much and in terms of alternate fuels, it is one of the less efficient fuels. Hybrid cars on the other hand have not really improved as a whole and individual cars can be seen varying in terms of efficiency. Overall, while we may think that we are getting better and more efficient cars, most cars have not improved throughout the years in terms of miles per gallon.
